title: Rights of women in conflict and fragile states
description:
Project background: In its early years, Grameen Sahara ran small-scale agricultural training programs among the tribal communities in Goalpara district of Assam. In 2007 the organization initiated the Golden Weavers’ Project, an Ericulture livelihood project, with support from Sir Dorabji TataTrust. In order to ensure optimum benefits to the community, Grameen Sahara subsequently incorporated an Eri Silk Producer Company in 2011, which is owned and run by the producers themselves. The organization also promotes and implements System of Crop Intensification (SCI) and Diversion Based Irrigation (DBI) in various areas of Assam. Through its microfinance operations, Grameen Sahara currently reaches around 27,000 families in the area. 
Project overview: This project is implemented as part of a new Grameen Sahara program that aims to promote sustainable livelihoods for the poor through the provision of financial services, technical assistance and other development support services in integrated manner. The specific objectives are to: improve the pace and quality of life of the rural and urban poor especially the village and decentralized sector; focus attention on women, children, the historically disadvantaged scheduled castes and scheduled tribes, minorities and other marginalized communities for their economic self-sustenance; create, develop and support self employment avenues for rural and urban youth; build social capital that will be used by and for the community; and optimally utilize all the available natural, social, economic and other resources for the well being of the community. 
Project activities and outputs: The project aims to facilitate the organization of producer groups of women weavers and spinners to address common problems such marketing, publicity, product diversification, skills upgrading. It will also provide capacity development support in the field of design development as well as working capital assistance towards purchase of raw materials. To address the scarcity of cocoons during the lean seasons, Grameen Sahara will also maintain a stock of cocoons to meet the needs of spinners. As a result of these activities, the project aims to contribute to higher and more predictable income for home-based women producers due to increased production and product quality This is expected to enhance the self respect and status of women in the community. By providing a steady supply of cocoons, the project will also help safeguard producers against market price fluctuations.

transaction_provider-org: Ministry of Foreign Affairs The Netherlands
title: Analysing scale up of biodiversity-based farming
description:
Centre for Sustainable Agriculture is a professional resource organization engaged in establishing models of sustainable agriculture working in partnership with NGOs and Community Based Organizations by scaling up the successes and engaging with the establishment for a policy change. 

CSA believes in promoting sustainable agricultural technologies that are based on farmers’ knowledge and skills, their innovation based on local conditions and their use of nature’s products and processes to gain better control over the pre-production and production processes involved in agriculture. CSA works with farmers to conserve their resources and their rights.

Great initiatives that build on agricultural biodiversity to increase resilience in farming systems can be found all over the world, but often they do not change things at a larger scale. Why is that? Why don't they make a bigger difference? How can we make sure that they have greater impact? A better understanding is needed of the factors that enable the successful scaling up of positive change for more resilient farming systems.

Developing a conceptual framework and criteria on good practice for agro-biodiversity based resilient farming, identifying cases where such practices have successfully reached scale and analysing their preconditions and impact, can generate insights that can help these solutions to transform from local islands of success into strategies that are transferable to other places and other contexts.

reporting-org: Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Cooperation, Spain
title: FORTALECIMIENTO DE LAS CAPACIDADES EDUCATIVAS DE LOS GRUPOS MÁS DESFAVORECIDOS DEL DISTRITO DE ANANTAPUR, A TRAVÉS DE LA CONSTRUCCIÓN DE CINCO ESCUELA
description: "El presente proyecto consiste en proporcionar a las comunidades de P. Kothapalli, Nallaiahkuntapalli, A.B. Palli Thanda, Pathapalyam, Ganthimarri, cinco escuelas con el doble uso de ser también espacios de reuniones comunitarias. La escuela de cada una de las aldeas constituirá un espacio digno y adecuado para impartir una educación complementaria, gratuita y de calidad a niños y niñas dálits, de grupos tribales y de las castas bajas; pero también se convertirá en el centro social y lugar de reuniones de los movimientos asociativos dentro de la comunidad. Así, la escuela y centro comunitario contribuirá a reforzar un sentimiento nuevo de unidad y de cohesión basado en un proyecto común en el que participan todas las familias de la comunidad, en el que todos y todas tienen voz y voto. Estas escuelas funcionan de forma paralela a las escuelas de gobierno, reforzando la educación de los niños y niñas de las castas más bajas para que puedan integrarse adecuadamente en los sistemas formales de educación, asegurando que puedan terminar con éxito la educación primaria y secundaria."

transaction_receiver-org: ROSI foundation(Rural organising for social improvement)
title: Help a young widow's self business and dignity
description: Training on Garments Making and sewing machine provision to each of 115 widow women for their income generation and sustainable survival.The destitute widow women will have 6 months training on Tailoring and EDP. Then a sewing machine and accessories are given to all.
participating-org (Implementing): ROSI foundation(Rural organising for social improvement)

transaction_provider-org: International Bank for Reconstruction and Development
title: IN Punjab Rural Water Sector Imprv Proje
description: The Punjab Rural Water and Sanitation Sector Improvement Project  of India has an objective to improve water and sanitation service levels, reduce open defecation, and strengthen service delivery arrangements in targeted villages in Punjab. The project will have four components with beneficiary villages or households selected using the objective criteria. Component one will provide approximately 570 villages with poor water services and/or partially covered status will be upgraded under Subcomponent 1(a) to receive service standards similar to urban areas (10 hours water supply per day, 100 percent household connections, volumetric charging) thus triggering a transformation in village living conditions. Component two will benefit women and marginalized communities who currently do not have access to water and sanitation (toilet) in the household within existing schemes. Component three will begin to address the water quality problems that are now becoming more apparent rendering Punjab one of the most quality affected states in India. Component four will support non-infrastructure project costs.
participating-org (Accountable): DEPARTMENT OF DRINKING WATER SUPPLY AND SANITATION, GOVERNME

title: Project Access (XRCVC)
description: The project aims at 4 major objectives, namely, bringing about amendment to Indian Copyright Act, 1957; To bring about financial access to the visually impaired in particular and disabled in general; to open up various mainstream educational courses that are hitherto unavailable to visually impaired students and to facilitate independent living by advocating for creation of enabling environment in areas like transport, infrastructure access, etc.  Both the above projects are well on their objectives.
participating-org (Implementing): Xaviers Resource Centre for Visually Challenged, Mumbai, India

title: National Dairy Support Project
description: The development objectives of the National Dairy Support Project for India are to increase the productivity of milch animals and improve market access of milk producers in project areas. Under this restructuring, a partial cancellation, at the request of the Recipient, of United States (U.S.) 97 million dollars equivalent is presented to reflect cost savings due to exchange rate fluctuation.

Under this restructuring, a partial cancellation, at the request of the Recipient, of United States (U.S.) 97 million dollars equivalent is presented to reflect cost savings due to exchange rate fluctuation.

reporting-org: Foreign Affairs, Trade and Development Canada (DFATD)
title: Canadian Co-operative Association - Program 2007-2011
description: This program aims to help poor households to improve their education and increase their income and assets by working through cooperatives, thereby enhancing their quality of life. The Canadian Co-operative Association (CCA) and its international partners are committed to developing gender-equitable opportunities and empowering poor women and men through the development of sustainable member-owned institutions that serve as a conduit for communities to develop themselves. The program is built on three principles: (1) ensuring holistic development by promoting sustainable livelihoods, (2) concentrating on cooperatives as key transformative structures for development, and (3) developing gender-equitable opportunities and empowerment within communities as a strategy for poverty reduction.     CIDA has provided $437,920 in additional support to this program for activities in Africa.
sector: Promotion of development awareness;Small and medium-sized enterprises (SME) development;Agricultural co-operatives;Business support services and institutions;Education/training in banking and financial services;Informal/semi-formal financial intermediaries;Democratic participation and civil society

description: This program aims to help poor households to improve their education and increase their income and assets by working through cooperatives, thereby enhancing their quality of life. The Canadian Co-operative Association (CCA) and its international partners are committed to developing gender-equitable opportunities and empowering poor women and men through the development of sustainable member-owned institutions that serve as a conduit for communities to develop themselves. The program is built on three principles: (1) ensuring holistic development by promoting sustainable livelihoods, (2) concentrating on cooperatives as key transformative structures for development, and (3) developing gender-equitable opportunities and empowerment within communities as a strategy for poverty reduction.     CIDA has provided $437,920 in additional support to this program for activities in Africa.
sector: Promotion of development awareness;Small and medium-sized enterprises (SME) development;Agricultural co-operatives;Business support services and institutions;Education/training in banking and financial services;Informal/semi-formal financial intermediaries;Democratic participation and civil society

CIDA has provided $437,920 in additional support to this program for activities in Africa.

reporting-org: Foreign Affairs, Trade and Development Canada (DFATD)
title: Canadian Co-operative Association - Program 2007-2011
description: This program aims to help poor households to improve their education and increase their income and assets by working through cooperatives, thereby enhancing their quality of life. The Canadian Co-operative Association (CCA) and its international partners are committed to developing gender-equitable opportunities and empowering poor women and men through the development of sustainable member-owned institutions that serve as a conduit for communities to develop themselves. The program is built on three principles: (1) ensuring holistic development by promoting sustainable livelihoods, (2) concentrating on cooperatives as key transformative structures for development, and (3) developing gender-equitable opportunities and empowerment within communities as a strategy for poverty reduction.     CIDA has provided $437,920 in additional support to this program for activities in Africa.

The Canadian Co-operative Association (CCA) and its international partners are committed to developing gender-equitable opportunities and empowering poor women and men through the development of sustainable member-owned institutions that serve as a conduit for communities to develop themselves. The program is built on three principles: (1) ensuring holistic development by promoting sustainable livelihoods, (2) concentrating on cooperatives as key transformative structures for development, and (3) developing gender-equitable opportunities and empowerment within communities as a strategy for poverty reduction.     CIDA has provided $437,920 in additional support to this program for activities in Africa.
sector: Promotion of development awareness;Small and medium-sized enterprises (SME) development;Agricultural co-operatives;Business support services and institutions;Education/training in banking and financial services;Informal/semi-formal financial intermediaries;Democratic participation and civil society

description: This program aims to help poor households to improve their education and increase their income and assets by working through cooperatives, thereby enhancing their quality of life. The Canadian Co-operative Association (CCA) and its international partners are committed to developing gender-equitable opportunities and empowering poor women and men through the development of sustainable member-owned institutions that serve as a conduit for communities to develop themselves. The program is built on three principles: (1) ensuring holistic development by promoting sustainable livelihoods, (2) concentrating on cooperatives as key transformative structures for development, and (3) developing gender-equitable opportunities and empowerment within communities as a strategy for poverty reduction.     CIDA has provided $437,920 in additional support to this program for activities in Africa.
sector: Promotion of development awareness;Small and medium-sized enterprises (SME) development;Agricultural co-operatives;Business support services and institutions;Education/training in banking and financial services;Informal/semi-formal financial intermediaries;Democratic participation and civil society

CIDA has provided $437,920 in additional support to this program for activities in Africa.

reporting-org: Foreign Affairs, Trade and Development Canada (DFATD)
title: Canadian Co-operative Association - Program 2007-2011
description: This program aims to help poor households to improve their education and increase their income and assets by working through cooperatives, thereby enhancing their quality of life. The Canadian Co-operative Association (CCA) and its international partners are committed to developing gender-equitable opportunities and empowering poor women and men through the development of sustainable member-owned institutions that serve as a conduit for communities to develop themselves. The program is built on three principles: (1) ensuring holistic development by promoting sustainable livelihoods, (2) concentrating on cooperatives as key transformative structures for development, and (3) developing gender-equitable opportunities and empowerment within communities as a strategy for poverty reduction.     CIDA has provided $437,920 in additional support to this program for activities in Africa.

The Canadian Co-operative Association (CCA) and its international partners are committed to developing gender-equitable opportunities and empowering poor women and men through the development of sustainable member-owned institutions that serve as a conduit for communities to develop themselves. The program is built on three principles: (1) ensuring holistic development by promoting sustainable livelihoods, (2) concentrating on cooperatives as key transformative structures for development, and (3) developing gender-equitable opportunities and empowerment within communities as a strategy for poverty reduction.     CIDA has provided $437,920 in additional support to this program for activities in Africa.
sector: Promotion of development awareness;Small and medium-sized enterprises (SME) development;Agricultural co-operatives;Business support services and institutions;Education/training in banking and financial services;Informal/semi-formal financial intermediaries;Democratic participation and civil society

description: This program aims to help poor households to improve their education and increase their income and assets by working through cooperatives, thereby enhancing their quality of life. The Canadian Co-operative Association (CCA) and its international partners are committed to developing gender-equitable opportunities and empowering poor women and men through the development of sustainable member-owned institutions that serve as a conduit for communities to develop themselves. The program is built on three principles: (1) ensuring holistic development by promoting sustainable livelihoods, (2) concentrating on cooperatives as key transformative structures for development, and (3) developing gender-equitable opportunities and empowerment within communities as a strategy for poverty reduction.     CIDA has provided $437,920 in additional support to this program for activities in Africa.
sector: Promotion of development awareness;Small and medium-sized enterprises (SME) development;Agricultural co-operatives;Business support services and institutions;Education/training in banking and financial services;Informal/semi-formal financial intermediaries;Democratic participation and civil society

CIDA has provided $437,920 in additional support to this program for activities in Africa.

reporting-org: Foreign Affairs, Trade and Development Canada (DFATD)
title: Canadian Co-operative Association - Program 2007-2011
description: This program aims to help poor households to improve their education and increase their income and assets by working through cooperatives, thereby enhancing their quality of life. The Canadian Co-operative Association (CCA) and its international partners are committed to developing gender-equitable opportunities and empowering poor women and men through the development of sustainable member-owned institutions that serve as a conduit for communities to develop themselves. The program is built on three principles: (1) ensuring holistic development by promoting sustainable livelihoods, (2) concentrating on cooperatives as key transformative structures for development, and (3) developing gender-equitable opportunities and empowerment within communities as a strategy for poverty reduction. title: SECOND INDIA INFRASTRUCTURE PROJECT FINANCING FACILITY-TRANCE 3
description:
The executing agency for the Second India Infrastructure Project Financing Facility (IIPFF II), the India Infrastructure Finance Company Limited (IIFCL), requested ADB to approve the Tranche III (Periodic Financing Request [PFR]3) of IIPFF II for $240 million to finance 7 indicative new subprojects in addition to the disbursement balance left for 5 existing subprojects approved under Tranches I and II. The total cost of the 7 subprojects is estimated at Rs140.18 billion (or $2.92 billion), inclusive of taxes, duties, and interest and other charges on the loan during construction, against which IIFCL sanctioned Rs15.2 billion (or $316.27 million). The PFR3 is expected to catalyze 12 times of funding resources from the market.  

The requested loan of $240 million will be from ADB's ordinary capital resources under ADB's LIBOR-based lending facility with a 0.15% commitment charge and a 25-year term including grace period of 5 years, and such other terms agreed in the FFA and under the loan agreement. The last date on which any disbursement request under this tranche is expected to be made on 14 December 2014.

IIFCL's project management unit (PMU), established under the IIPFF I, will continue to monitor day-to-day implementation of Tranche III including the identification, screening, selection, and monitoring of all subprojects, including compliance with state and national policies and the environmental and social safeguard framework. The indicative 7 subprojects under the proposed PFR3 were selected based on commercial and technical viability in compliance with relevant national and ADB norms. The tranche's loan proceeds will be disbursed in accordance with ADB's Loan Disbursement Handbook (2007, as amended from time to time). IIFCL requested retroactive financing for the PFR3. Except as otherwise agreed with ADB, it is proposed that the total eligible expenditure under retroactive financing will not exceed an amount equivalent to 20% of the individual loan and must have been incurred not more than 12 months before signing of the related legal agreements.

reporting-org: Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland
title: The dissemination of clean-burning pyrolytic stoves in Greater Mumbai
description: CED will produce together with Social Activities Integration 30 000 improved cooking stoves and replace one third of the 100 000 most polluting cooking stoves in the Greater Mumbai area with them. If this first stage of the project will be succesfull CED will apply further funding for two other 3-year continuation projects the aim of which is to replace also the remaining highly polluting stoves with SAI stoves (=extremely clean-burning stoves planned and designed by the world- famous improved stoves expert Saibashkar Nakka Reddy together with the SAI personnel). If the project and its continuation phases will succeed in replacing the 100 000 most polluting cooking stoves in the Greater Mumbai areas with SAI stoves this should both benefit the 100 000 poorest households in the area (because they will need less cooking energy) and improve the air quality in an area inhabited by more than 20 million people.  We do not have precise numbers but it seems likely (obvious) that the mentioned 100 000 highly polluting cooking stoves are responsible for a significant perecentage of all parcticulate emissions released into the air in the Greater Mumbai area. The 100 000 highly polluting stoves cannot be replaced with better stoves without subsidizing the production because they are used by the poorest households that cannot afford kerosene electricity or liquid gas and that have not this far even been able to invest in better coing stoves. According to our prior experience (based on 2 500 SAI stoves that have already been manufactured and sold for the poor households in Mumbai by SAI) the poor families will by and adopt improved clean-burning and energy-saving stoves if their price is reduced to an affordable level (from their perspective) with a subsidy of 5 or 5.5 euros per cooking stove. This means that might be possible to significantly improve the air quality in the Greater Mumbai region by investing 0.025 euros per inhabitant in subsidies on improved cooking stoves sold for the poor families.  Or at least SAI our cooperation partner in Mumbai thinks that it would be possible to achieve something like this with approximately 500 000 euros in 9-10 years.
participating-org (Extending): Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland

IN: Bihar Social Protection
description: The development objective of the Bihar Integrated Social Protection Strengthening Project for India is to strengthen institutional capacity of the Department of Social Welfare and the Rural Development Department to deliver social protection programs and services and expand outreach of social care services for poor and vulnerable households, persons with disabilities, older persons, and widows in the state of Bihar. The project has two components: the first component, strengthening social protection systems and capacity will strengthen core systems and capacity of the Bihar Rural Development Society (BRDS) and the State Society for Ultra-Poor and Social Welfare (SSUPSW), which are the program implementation arms of the Rural Development Department and the Department of Social Welfare respectively, at the state, district, and block levels. This component has two sub-components: (i) strengthening systems and capacity for safety net delivery; and (ii) strengthening systems and capacity for social pension and social care service delivery. The second component is establish and strengthen social care services. This component will support establishing social care services across the state through social care service centers (referred to as Buniyad centers) that will provide high quality care, support, and rehabilitation services for older persons, widows, and persons with disabilities. It has following three sub-components: (i) establish and strengthen social care services; (ii) pilot models in social protection delivery; and (iii) innovation window.
participating-org (Accountable): RURAL DEVELOPMENT DEPT (GOB) & SOCIAL WELFARE DEPT (GOB)
participating-org (Implementing): RURAL DEVELOPMENT DEPT (GOB) & SOCIAL WELFARE DEPT (GOB)

transaction_receiver-org: MOHAN ( Multi Organ Harvesting Aid network ) FOUNDATION
title: Training to augment organ donation in India
description: This project will support the invaluable task of training 100 Transplant Coordinators who do the unenviable job of counseling bereaved families to encourage them to donate the organs of their deceased loved one and save other lives.  Speaking to families who have just lost a dear one is no easy task and needs to be done with sensitivity which the coordinators are trained for in addition to coordinating the entire process of donation and transplant in a timely  and effective manner.

transaction_receiver-org: indian multi purpose trust for the blind
title: COMPUTER TRAINING CENTRE FOR VISUALLY IMPAIRED
description: In the commercial and social scenario there is a wide scope of employment opportunities available for the partial and completely blind people in both government and private sectors.  Computer centers that provide training to these visually impaired people using a special software "JAWS" are very few and situated in proper city and are incapable of serving to a large number of such people who reside away from the main city in the rural areas.

reporting-org: Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Cooperation, Spain
title: ?Fortalecimiento de las capacidades educativas de los grupos más desfavorecidos del distrito de Anantapur, a través de la construcción de cinco escuel
description: "?Fortalecimiento de las capacidades educativas de los grupos más desfavorecidos del distrito de Anantapur, a través de la construcción de cinco escuelas de primaria? :: El proyecto consiste en proporcionar a cinco comunidades del distrito de Anantapur de cinco nuevos edificios que van a funcionar con el doble uso de escuela y centro comunitario. Este edificio constituirá un espacio digno y adecuado para impartir una educación complementaria, gratuita y de calidad a niños y niñas dálits, de grupos tribales y de las castas bajas; pero también se convertirá en el centro social y de reuniones de las comunidades. Así, la escuela y centro comunitario contribuirá a reforzar un sentimiento nuevo de unidad y de cohesión basado en un proyecto común en el que participan todas las familias de la comunidad, en el que todos y todas tienen voz y voto Los/las beneficiarios/as del proyecto son mujeres, hombres, niñas y niños de las comunidades rurales pertenecientes a los grupos sociales más discriminados y excluidos por el sistema de castas hindú, que regula las relaciones sociales en India desde hace más de 3.500 años: los dálits, las castas bajas y los grupos tribales. OBJETIVO GENERAL Mejorada la situación educativa infantil y el nivel de integración social de los dálits, castas bajas y grupos tribales de la población del distrito de Anantapur, La India OBJETIVO ESPECIFICO Incrementados los niveles educativos de 421 menores desfavorecidos de las comunidades rurales de J. Kothapalli, K.Sivaram, Mylepalli, Ankampalli y Talikera por medio de la construcción de 5 escuelas complementarias."

title: KOLKATA ENVIRONMENTAL IMPROVEMENT PROJECT
description: The supplementary loan will support KMC in achieving the scope and objectives of the original Project. The Project will continue to: (i) improve the environmental conditions in the outer areas of Kolkata; (ii) reduce poverty in the low-income areas through affordable access to basic urban services; (iii) facilitate community empowerment through participatory processes; (iv) protect the environment from adverse developmental impacts; and (v) help KMC develop as a proficient and autonomous municipality. The Project will contribute to achieving the targets of Millennium Development Goal.

title: KOLKATA ENVIRONMENTAL IMPROVEMENT PROJECT
description: The supplementary loan will support KMC in achieving the scope and objectives of the original Project. The Project will continue to: (i) improve the environmental conditions in the outer areas of Kolkata; (ii) reduce poverty in the low-income areas through affordable access to basic urban services; (iii) facilitate community empowerment through participatory processes; (iv) protect the environment from adverse developmental impacts; and (v) help KMC develop as a proficient and autonomous municipality. The Project will contribute to achieving the targets of Millennium Development Goal.

title: SUPPORTING KERALA'S ADDITIONAL SKILL ACQUISITION PROGRAM IN POST-BASIC EDUCATION
description: The Kerala State Skill Development Project was launched by the Government of Kerala (GOK) in July 2012 to enhance the employability of the state's youth and create opportunities for productive employment. It has two sub-programs to tackle the supply-side problems. The first, the Additional Skill Acquisition Program (ASAP), has been designed by the Departments of Higher Education and General Education, GOK to address the preventive dimension of low employability. The second, the Additional Skill Enhancement Program, has been designed by the Department of Labor and Employment and the Department of Local Self Government, GOK to address the curative dimension by focusing on re-skilling the unemployed youths registered with employment exchanges. The Government of India and GOK have requested Asian Development Bank assistance for strengthening and scaling up ASAP since it aims to tackle the problem of low employability early on by integrating general and vocational education so that students become market-ready even while being enrolled in school and college. The impact will be increased employment of Kerala 's youth. The outcome is that the graduates of government and government-aided higher secondary schools and arts-science colleges are more employable.This will be achieved by the following outputs: (i) market-relevant vocational training introduced in post-basic education, (ii) access to quality vocational training enhanced, (iii) increased awareness and private sector participation facilitated, (iv) improved program management and monitoring and evaluation.
participating-org (Accountable): Department of Higher Education, Government of Kerala
participating-org (Implementing): Department of Higher Education, Government of Kerala

title: ROOTS: Repositioning Man-Agriculture Link within the Biosphere-Towards Sustainable Nutritional Security
description: The programme 'ROOTS' aims to establish a symbiotic relationship between the human and biosphere with a focus to bring out the links between conservation and sustainable human development. through repositioning the traditional farming practices in the modern context which can be used for ensuring food and nutritional security. Acknowledging the need to rediscover and reposition Man-Agriculture link within the Biosphere, the programme proposes to establish a sustainable, holistic food security system in the region. The first part of the programme which was basically a 'Consultative Phase' was implemented by organizing an international workshop from 3-5 May 2011 at CIMP, Patna, India. During the current phase, documentation of the process and dissemination of results will be attempted.

title: ANCP Innovations Fund 2009-10 to 2012-13
description: The Australia Non Government Organisations Cooperation Program (ANCP) Innovations Fund is a competitive subsidy scheme for accredited Australian Non-Government Organisations (NGOs). The fund is designed to assist in the implementation of NGOs own innovative development activities while supporting shared learning and collaboration across the international development sector. The ANCP Innovations Fund was part of a suite of reforms to the ANCP. The total value of this multi-country  initiative is $4.5 million over 4 years, starting 2009-10.

title: Establishment of a womens wing and support to women learning centres in Andhra Pradesh
description:
FFA-AP is the Federation of farmers' organisations in Andhra Pradesh India. It represents 1800 farmers' associations on the local level spread over 14 (of the 22 districts). Membership is about 69.000 farmers.

      FFA-AP started women specific activities in 2007, by strengthening existing self help Groups and establishing 55 women learning centres at village level.

      The present project submitted to Agriterra comes down to:
      - income generating activities for women in 3 districts with an outreach of 1800 women per year
      - establishment of a women's wing within FFA-AP

title: IN: Industrial Pollution Management
description: The development objective of the Capacity Building for Industrial Pollution Management Project for India is twofold: (i) to support the development of institutional and methodological framework for rehabilitation of highly polluted sites, resulting from rapid industrialization and which is piloted in two states; and (ii) to build tangible human and technical capacity in state agencies for undertaking projects for reducing the risks from contamination to population, livelihood, and ecosystem, associated with past environmental damage. This restructuring will bring the following changes: (a) cancellation of special drawing rights (SDR) 6.49 million (United States (U.S.) 10 million dollars equivalent) of the total SDR 25.70 million (U.S. 38.94 million dollars equivalent) in the International Development Association (IDA) credit for the project; (b) the exchange rate of Indian rupee (Rs.) has depreciated from Rs.44.94 (at the project appraisal in May, 2010) to 62.48 (as on November 30, 2013) as against the dollar. This partial cancellation will allow the Department of Economic Affairs (DEA) to reallocate the funds under IDA 16; and (c) about SDR 97,100 also remained unclaimed under project preparation advance (category two) of the project. This is to be transferred to 'category one (b)' of eligible expenditures.

transaction_provider-org: International Bank for Reconstruction and Development
title: IN: Industrial Pollution Management
description: The development objective of the Capacity Building for Industrial Pollution Management Project for India is twofold: (i) to support the development of institutional and methodological framework for rehabilitation of highly polluted sites, resulting from rapid industrialization and which is piloted in two states; and (ii) to build tangible human and technical capacity in state agencies for undertaking projects for reducing the risks from contamination to population, livelihood, and ecosystem, associated with past environmental damage. This restructuring will bring the following changes: (a) cancellation of special drawing rights (SDR) 6.49 million (United States (U.S.) 10 million dollars equivalent) of the total SDR 25.70 million (U.S. 38.94 million dollars equivalent) in the International Development Association (IDA) credit for the project; (b) the exchange rate of Indian rupee (Rs.) has depreciated from Rs.44.94 (at the project appraisal in May, 2010) to 62.48 (as on November 30, 2013) as against the dollar. This partial cancellation will allow the Department of Economic Affairs (DEA) to reallocate the funds under IDA 16; and (c) about SDR 97,100 also remained unclaimed under project preparation advance (category two) of the project. This is to be transferred to 'category one (b)' of eligible expenditures.
participating-org (Funding): International Bank for Reconstruction and Development
participating-org (Extending): International Bank for Reconstruction and Development
sector-vocabulary: ;;;;OECD Development Assistance Committee;OECD Development Assistance Committee

transaction_description: Total Interest Repayment in Fourth Quarter of 2013
title: IN: Industrial Pollution Management
description: The development objective of the Capacity Building for Industrial Pollution Management Project for India is twofold: (i) to support the development of institutional and methodological framework for rehabilitation of highly polluted sites, resulting from rapid industrialization and which is piloted in two states; and (ii) to build tangible human and technical capacity in state agencies for undertaking projects for reducing the risks from contamination to population, livelihood, and ecosystem, associated with past environmental damage. This restructuring will bring the following changes: (a) cancellation of special drawing rights (SDR) 6.49 million (United States (U.S.) 10 million dollars equivalent) of the total SDR 25.70 million (U.S. 38.94 million dollars equivalent) in the International Development Association (IDA) credit for the project; (b) the exchange rate of Indian rupee (Rs.) has depreciated from Rs.44.94 (at the project appraisal in May, 2010) to 62.48 (as on November 30, 2013) as against the dollar. This partial cancellation will allow the Department of Economic Affairs (DEA) to reallocate the funds under IDA 16; and (c) about SDR 97,100 also remained unclaimed under project preparation advance (category two) of the project. This is to be transferred to 'category one (b)' of eligible expenditures.

participating-org (Extending): International Bank for Reconstruction and Development

transaction_provider-org: International Bank for Reconstruction and Development
title: IN: NHAI Technical Assistance Project
description: The project development objective of National Highways Authority of India (NHAI) is to assist to adopt the appropriate practices that would enhance its program management and operational efficiency. There are three components to the project. The first component of the project is program level technical support which includes preparation of a project preparation manual and improvement of environmental and social policies and procedures. The second component of the project is institutional strengthening and capacity building which includes implementation of enterprise resource planning and preparation and implementation of a comprehensive exposure and training plan for NHAI staff including twining arrangements with agencies/institutions of repute abroad. And the third component of the project is technology and innovation which includes implementation of the Nandan Nilekani committee recommendations on Nation-wide tolling strategy and interoperability of toll collection systems and partnership and support to research and training institutions of the sector in India.
participating-org (Funding): International Bank for Reconstruction and Development
participating-org (Extending): International Bank for Reconstruction and Development

title: SUPPORTING HUMAN CAPITAL DEVELOPMENT IN MEGHALAYA
description: The project will enhance the employability of Meghalaya’s youth (16–35 years old) by improving the quality, access, and delivery of its secondary and higher secondary (SHS) education, and technical and vocational skills development programs. The project will (i) improve teaching and learning in government-aided secondary and higher secondary schools, (ii) increased capacity and responsiveness of technical and vocational  education and training, (iii) increase awareness of students and participation of NGOs, and (iv) improve project management and monitoring and evaluation through providing technical support to implement project activities and build capacity; and  hiring a research institute or consulting firm to undertake skills-gap analysis and tracer studies to track the results of skills training and learning reforms.
sector-vocabulary: Reporting Organisation (i.e. maintained by the organisation referred to in the <reporting-org> element.

reporting-org: Foreign Affairs, Trade and Development Canada (DFATD)
title: Reduction of Avoidable Blindness Program
description: This program aims to prevent blindness by focussing on: community-based prevention and community development, restoring sight among the curable blind, as well as training eye care professionals and local health promoters. This program contributes mainly to addressing health care priorities, but also works to reduce poverty and improve the social integration of visually impaired people.
sector: Promotion of development awareness;Basic health infrastructure;Basic health care

description: This program aims to prevent blindness by focussing on: community-based prevention and community development, restoring sight among the curable blind, as well as training eye care professionals and local health promoters. description: This program aims to prevent blindness by focussing on: community-based prevention and community development, restoring sight among the curable blind, as well as training eye care professionals and local health promoters. description: This program aims to prevent blindness by focussing on: community-based prevention and community development, restoring sight among the curable blind, as well as training eye care professionals and local health promoters. description: This program aims to prevent blindness by focussing on: community-based prevention and community development, restoring sight among the curable blind, as well as training eye care professionals and local health promoters. This program contributes mainly to addressing health care priorities, but also works to reduce poverty and improve the social integration of visually impaired people.
sector: Promotion of development awareness;Basic health infrastructure;Basic health care

title: Accelerate adoption of energy efficient appliances through consumer rebate scheme in a distribution utility
description:
To support the design of a mechanism to scale up adoption of energy efficient appliances (specifically fridges
and air conditioners), including with a demonstrated replacement of 15,000 old inefficient
appliances with new energy efficient ones.

reporting-org: Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Cooperation, Spain
title: Mejora de la salud reproductiva de las mujeres de la región de Kalyandurg, distrito de Anantapur, India
description: "El objeto del convenio es articular la colaboración entre la Agencia vasca de Cooperación para el Desarrollo y la Fundación Vicente Ferrer para la cofinanciación de un programa que tiene como objeto la mejora de la salud reproductiva de las mujeres en la región de Kalyandurg, distrito de Anantapur, en la India 1º Incrementarlos nivels de la salud maternal en todas sus fases - prenatal, alumbramiento y post-parto de las mujeres a las que va dirigido el programa. 2º Disminuir los niveles de mortalidad y morbilidad maternal. 3º Mejorar y facilitar el acceso de esas mujeres a servicios ginecológicos asequibles y de calidad, a través de los prestados por el Hospital de Kalyandurg y por la red de asistencia rural. 4º Mejorar los conocimientos sobre prácticas saludables en relación a la salud reproductiva y sexual de las mujeres de la región de Kalyandurg a través de a transmisión de la información oportuna"

title: From Child Labour to a Chance at School
description: The project works with child laborers who live on construction sites with their parents and are migrants. These children have no access to education and are living in hazardous environment at sites. We aim to connect these children back to mainstream education by providing informal education &basic nutrition support.Every year we support around 250 children & to date we have enrolled more than 1,703 child laborer in our CFS classes and have steered around 195 of these children to formal school

title: Green Riders moving out of poverty in Bihar India
description: This is a simple straightforward appeal to provide cycle rickshaws to  below the poverty line families in order to provide a vital source of income. If Bihar was a country it would be the sixth poorest in the world and a regular source of Income can make all the difference to a family struggling to put food on the table. We will provide uniforms, ID cards, basic training in English , and a brand new cycle rickshaw. One rickshaw can earn enough daily to provide 7 kg rice or 5 kg vegetables.

title: MFF-ORISSA INTEGRATED IRRIGATED AGRI & WATER MGT INV PROG-PRJ1
description: The Project aims to (i) enhance productivity and sustainability of existing underutilized and underperforming major, medium, and minor irrigation systems with participatory irrigation management, and (ii) strengthen institutions for sustainable irrigation service delivery and associated support services, and for initiating operations for integrated water resources management on the basis of river basins. Its tentative scope includes (i) participatory scheme design and WUA strengthening; (ii) irrigation and associated infrastructure; (iii) agriculture and fishery development support; (iv) establishing sustainable O&M mechanisms; and (iv) institutional strengthening and project management.

title: India Pure it
description: Project will further the mission of protecting lives by providing access to safe drinking water amongst poor households who cannot afford to pay the price for a purifier upfront.   HUL expects Dharma Life to protect at least 1250 homes initially and thereafter continue to protect additional 2000 homes every year with the grant provided. PSI will utilise the HUL grant by providing a service delivery contract of Rs. 46.75 lakhs (Including Service Tax) to Dharma Life to run a program for providing consumer financing to poor households through its village level entrepreneurs.

title: CPA UK Parliamentarians visit to India (1-7 April 2013 and 17-23 February 2014)
description: Visit of UK MPs in April 2013 and February 2014 with the purpose of  meeting with Indian Members of Parliament  for a better understanding of UK and India Parliamentary systems. Indian MPs discuss aspects of UK systems which they could apply to India. The visit is aimed at promoting good governance in India through a focus on parliament and parliamentary ethics.

transaction_receiver-org: (Chief, Administrative Services) for and on behalf of Centre for Policy Research Registered Society
title: Institutional Support to Policy Research Organizations in India
description:
IDRC's Think Tank Initiative is a multi-donor program dedicated to strengthening independent policy research institutions, or "think tanks," in developing countries, thereby enabling them to produce sound research that both informs and influences policy. The Initiative selected the first cohort of 24 grantees in East and West Africa through a competitive call in 2008-2009. A second competitive call was launched in 2009, targeting seven countries in Latin America and five countries in South Asia (Bangladesh, India, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka). Of the 16 successful applicants from South Asia, nine are in India.

Policy research in South Asia is dominated by India. A long tradition of independent research exists there thanks to the strong demand from policymakers in search  of ideas and advice. Local funding is available, but as in other regions, this tends to be project-based and is moving away from support to the social sciences. Institutions are struggling to maintain high quality research and to communicate their results effectively.

This grant will strengthen the ability of the nine research institutions in India to provide, disseminate and communicate high-quality research. It will do so through measures aimed at enhancing the ability of staff to conduct sound research, improving organizational performance and forging links with policymakers. Particular effort will be made to enable grantees to mobilize other sources of funding, so that none become dependent on the Think Tank Initiative over the long term. The project will also support a platform for grantee networking both within the Initiative and with a wider network of institutions engaged in policy-related research.

title: BIHAR STATE HIGHWAYS II PROJECT
description: The Bihar State Highways II Project  will build and upgrade about 389 kilometers (km) of state highways identified under the State Highway Development Program in Bihar. It will involve upgrading roads to two lanes, strengthening culverts and bridges, building new road sections and bridges and cross drainage structures, and building structures for resettlement and rehabilitation. Consulting support will be provided to support implementation of civil works.

title: support for HIV positive orphans and widows
description: The social dynamics of Indian state of Uttarakhand in the Himalayas is affected by out migration of males and a 'post office' economy.Because of migration of male productive age group  to the big cities, staying away from the family , they get involve in multiple sex partners  are high risk group of  HIV/AIDS and mortality in young age .this project will provide  nutritional support, transportation to 16 HIV orphans and 24 widows for   ART, treatment for opportunistic infections and awareness.

title: Inclusive and gender-responsive quality literacy programmes in South Asia
description: The activity contributes to C/5 Expected Result 2, where support will be provided to the South Asian countries (Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, and Nepal) in the implementation of their commitments to intensify efforts to achieve their literacy goals by 2015 and to envision the literacy agenda beyond 2015. Expected Result: National capacities and partnerships strengthened to scale up development relevant and gender-responsive quality literacy programmes. Key outputs/deliverables: policy reviews/research to scale-up effective youth and adult literacy programmes, with a focus on women; reinforced partnership of the stakeholders at all levels to support out-of-school children literacy provision.

title: IN:Orissa Community Tank Management Proj
description: The development objective of the Orissa Community Tank Management Project for India is for selected tank based producers to improve agricultural productivity and water user associations to manage tank systems effectively. This restructuring will bring the following changes: (i) a partial cancellation, at the request of the Recipient of Unites States (U.S.) 10 million dollars equivalent to reflect cost savings due to exchange rate fluctuation; and (ii) extension of the closing date for a period of 22 months from August 31, 2014 to June 30, 2016.

title: IN:Orissa Community Tank Management Proj

title: Assistive technology - Vision Aid
description:
The project aims to create an atmosphere whereby the Visually Impaired (VI) are provided with training for personal development, career enhancement, bring in a facilitative environment and to train teachers of the VI children so that they are able to provide this training to their students in schools. 

The programme focuses on providing computer skill training to the VIs from Vizag and the neighbouring sub districts. It also supports colleges for setting up satellite training centres where VIs students are enrolled through which VI students are trained in computers. Besides, it trains the teachers and the students pursuing Bachelors of Education (B. Ed) with an aim that these individuals will further use the learn skills while teaching VI students. Also a resource centre has been established under this project which has few computers that can be utilised by the students for practise and also has various devices for persons with blindness and Low Vision. This acts as a centre for creating awareness among the general public and also among those interested in working for people with VI.

title: Provide School Meals to Children in India
description: Everyday, Akshaya Patra provides hot, nutritious school meals to 1.4 million under-served children in more than 10,600 government schools across India from 23 kitchen facilities. For many children this is their only meal of the day, and it gives them the essential nutrients growing children need to develop cognitive abilities that enable them to excel in school.

title: Preventing school dropout of 400 children in India
description: This project would prevent school dropout of 400 children from extremely poverty stricken families, for both children residing in the Children's and Observation Homes and children discharged from these homes thereby eliminating the risks of dropout children (re)turning to crime or becoming child laborers.

transaction_provider-org: Ministry of Foreign Affairs The Netherlands
title: Campaigning for the Rights of Dalit Communities in Madhya Pradesh, India
description:
Jan Sahas Social Development Society (Jan Sahas) is an NGO working to ensure the rights and empowerment of marginalized communities, especially Dalits, in the central Indian state of Madhya Pradesh. 

Jan Sahas follows a participatory approach while monitoring and responding to discrimination and atrocities against marginalized communities, increasing awareness about their rights, promoting local-level leadership, and forming community-based organizations (CBOs). Jan Sahas has formed four thematic CBOs: a Dalit collective; a women’s collective for elimination of manual scavenging as well as the rescue and rehabilitation of those forced into the practice; a women’s collective; and a children’s collective. In this project the focus lies on Dalits, in particular women and children.

From 2014 to 2016 Jan Sahas will be implementing 3 campaigns with the support of UUHHJIF and Hivos. The Campaign for Establishing Right to Land addresses the issue of land rights for Dalits and Tribal communities in Madhya Pradesh, who make up over 35 percent of the population, but hold only 7 percent of arable land in the region. Historically, these groups have been deprived of land rights, but it is believed that equal distribution of land paves the way for positive social and economical changes in the community. The Campaign builds on land reforms done in 2002, promising to make land available to Dalit and Tribal groups. Steps have been made, but research has shown that 60 percent of families face various types of problems, both legal and agricultural. The Campaign seeks to support these groups in resolving the issues.

The second Campaign addresses atrocities and violence against Dalits and Women, who suffer disproportionate levels of various forms of physical assault (including killings, rape, arson) in Madhya Pradesh. Many of these go unreported, primarily because of police reluctance to register them. Cases that are registered often remain uninvestigated.  The Campaign seeks to address these issue, through ensuring access to justice to victims, and by filing cases with different authorities. 

The third Campaign is against discrimination and social exclusion focusing on education. Studies have shown that Dalits in Madhya Pradesh, due to their “untouchability”, face exclusion from many public places, including schools. This leads to low literacy rates amongst the group, and, despite education being a fundamental right, only 64.7 percent of Dalit children between 5 and 14 goes to school. The Campaigns focuses amongst other on sensitization on Dalit and non-Dalit groups alike, policy dialogue with various stakeholder and community monitoring on exclusion from education.

title: Gift a Happy Childhood to 30000 Children in India
description: 'It is easier to build strong children than to repair broken men.' Toybank envisions a world where all children are empowered through healthy play. It provides secure and happy childhoods for children who are at risk, so they are empowered to experience an equitable adulthood. Toybank believes that qualities like passion, enthusiasm and goodness are qualities which are planted at the root level. A happy Childhood defines so many aspects for children and thus the society at large.

title: Frame agreement with NGO (Fida Int.)
description: Maharashtra Village Development Project.Improved quality of life and self help attitude of people in Maharashtra rural areas. Especially farmers are suffering with circle of debt. Our partner is South India Assemblies of God. The Project partner has already established good relationship with the under privileges and downtrodden people in rural area is advantage to organize the community. The villagers are jobless and circle of debt turn the rural families in poor situation of all areas of basic needs! This situation pushes them to search for better life and migration from villages in to the urban areas like a Mumbai. Due to increase of migration_ they become slum and street dwellers that they never thought about it. We have conducted survey in 32 villages.  As per the survey the people lack of basic needs like food_ house_ water_ education_ sanitation_ health care etc. The rural women and the children are malnourished. The people are farmers and manual labourers. The Project committee is going to choose five pilot villages_ where the plan is start work during 2008. The purpose of work is to cover all areas of basic needs of the rural community in Maharashtra by CDE (Community Development Education) activities. To improve quality of life in their basic needs of rural community in Maharashtra which partly contributes to their social and economical status in the community.
sector: Multisector aid for basic social services

title: Empower girls with life skills: Create Leaders!
description: We empower girl students to form groups called Bal Sabhas or a Girls' Councils, which are elected democratically by all students in the school. The girls engage in role playing and storytelling, which leads to an increase in the participation and helps in developing critical thinking, problem solving, communication, leadership skills and many more. This year, our target is to prepare 5,070 girls in 390 schools to lead their life and their communities.

title: Enhanced Preservation of Fruits in South Asia (CIFSRF)
description:
India and Sri Lanka produce an abundance of vegetables and tropical fruits, but post-harvest losses are between 35 and 40%, valued at about $800 million annually. These losses affect the livelihoods of nearly one-third of the population, the majority of which are smallholder farmers. Past research to increase post-harvest shelf life has focused primarily on keeping fruit firm, which is unsuitable for tropical fruits such as mangoes. 

This project brings together research partners from Canada and South Asia to develop a nanotechnology-based packaging system that will extend the shelf life of fruits, thus augmenting local food and livelihood security.

The nano-particles in this project are developed from agricultural waste products, namely the natural fibres extracted from coconut husks and banana plants, creating new income opportunities for small-scale entrepreneurs, particularly women. The project is also building links with the private sector for biodegradable packaging materials.

Researchers expect to adapt the technologies developed in this project to other economically important horticultural crops, including flowers, and vegetables. Benefits for the soft fruit industry, such as berries, can also be extended to Canada.

This project is supported by IDRC and Foreign Affairs, Trade and Development Canada through the Canadian International Food Security Research Fund (CIFSRF).

Past research to increase post-harvest shelf life has focused primarily on keeping fruit firm, which is unsuitable for tropical fruits such as mangoes. 

This project brings together research partners from Canada and South Asia to develop a nanotechnology-based packaging system that will extend the shelf life of fruits, thus augmenting local food and livelihood security.

The nano-particles in this project are developed from agricultural waste products, namely the natural fibres extracted from coconut husks and banana plants, creating new income opportunities for small-scale entrepreneurs, particularly women. The project is also building links with the private sector for biodegradable packaging materials.

Researchers expect to adapt the technologies developed in this project to other economically important horticultural crops, including flowers, and vegetables. Benefits for the soft fruit industry, such as berries, can also be extended to Canada.

This project is supported by IDRC and Foreign Affairs, Trade and Development Canada through the Canadian International Food Security Research Fund (CIFSRF).

title: RFSU-MAMTA Nätverk
description: "Young People´s Health and Development" MAMTA-RFSU Network on adolescents sexual and reproductive health and rights in India. The overall goal is to create an enabling environment for improved health and development of young people through an integrated approach to reproductive and and sexual health especially of poorer section by promoting gender equality and rights.

title: Cyclone Phailine Response 2013-14
description:
Tropical Cyclone Phailin (Cyclone level 4 as per Indian Meteorological Department) made landfall in heavily populated Orissa coast on Saturday, the 12th October night with terrifying winds of 200-210km speed per hour. There was storm surge up to 3 meter height. Worst hit districts are Ganjam, Puri, Khurda, Cuttack, Jagatshingpur, Naygarh amongst the 17 affected districts in Orissa. Kalingapatnam, the adjacent district in the state of Andhra Pradesh was also affected by Cyclone Phailin.  Heavy rains brought by the cyclone Phailin that hit the coast on Saturday night led to flooding, causing a second crisis in Mayurbhanj, Balasore, Kendrapara, Bhadrak and Jajjpur district. The worst affected by flooding are the Balasore and Kendrapara district. Due to heavy precipitation, released water from the Hirakud dam has made the situation critical. Even as the life continued to remain out of gear in cyclone hit areas, the flood situation remained grim in 4 affected districts. There is full moon on 18th October; until then due to high tide the situation will remain worst. However, in Ganjam district, flood water has started receding since 16th October.

This Emergency Response is to provide immediate humanitarian assistance to decrease public health risks to 9750 cyclone-affected men women and children in Ganjam and Puri Districts through provision of water and sanitation facilities, public health services, emergency shelter and emergency food and livelihood assistance support by March 2013.

Specific outputs:
RESULT 1 # Water, sanitation and Hygiene (WASH)
RESULT 2 # Provide Emergency Food Security (EFSVL)
RESULT 3 # Emergency Shelter
